    <h2 class="subtitle" id="anatomy-eye">1. Anatomy of the Eye</h2>
    <div class="content">
        <p>This section explores the anatomy of the eye, with a particular focus on the human eye.</p>

        <h4>Key Parts of the Eye</h4>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Cornea:</strong> The clear, dome-shaped front layer that helps to focus light entering the eye.</li>
            <img src="Vision%20in%20Humans%20and%20Nocturnal%20Animals_files/cornea-diagram.jpg" alt="Diagram of the Cornea" class="img-fluid">
            
            <li><strong>Pupil:</strong> The adjustable opening in the 
center of the eye that regulates the amount of light that enters. The 
iris surrounds the pupil and controls its size.</li>
            <img src="Vision%20in%20Humans%20and%20Nocturnal%20Animals_files/pupil-diagram.jpg" alt="Diagram of the Pupil" class="img-fluid">
            
            <li><strong>Lens:</strong> A flexible structure that further
 focuses light onto the retina, adjusting its shape to help focus on 
objects at varying distances.</li>
            <img src="Vision%20in%20Humans%20and%20Nocturnal%20Animals_files/lens-diagram.jpg" alt="Diagram of the eye" class="img-fluid">

            <img src="Vision%20in%20Humans%20and%20Nocturnal%20Animals_files/human_eye.jpg" alt="Printer">
            
            <li><strong>Retina:</strong> A light-sensitive layer at the 
back of the eye containing photoreceptor cells (rods and cones) that 
convert light into electrical signals.
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Rods:</strong> Sensitive to low light levels, responsible for night vision.</li>
                    <li><strong>Cones:</strong> Responsible for color vision and function best in bright light.</li>
                    <img src="Vision%20in%20Humans%20and%20Nocturnal%20Animals_files/lens-diagram.jpg" alt="Cones and Rods" class="img-fluid">

                    <img src="Vision%20in%20Humans%20and%20Nocturnal%20Animals_files/cones.jpg" alt="Printer">

                    <p class="img-source">Source: American Academy of Ophthalmology</p>

                </ul>
            </li>
            <img src="Vision%20in%20Humans%20and%20Nocturnal%20Animals_files/retina-diagram.jpg" alt="Diagram of the Retina" class="img-fluid">
            
            <li><strong>Optic Nerve:</strong> Transmits visual information from the retina to the brain, where it is processed and interpreted as images.</li>
            <img src="Vision%20in%20Humans%20and%20Nocturnal%20Animals_files/optic-nerve-diagram.jpg" alt="Diagram of the Optic Nerve" class="img-fluid">
        </ul>

        <h3>Process of Vision</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Light Entry:</strong> Light enters through the cornea and pupil.</li>
            <li><strong>Focusing:</strong> The lens adjusts to focus light onto the retina.</li>
            <li><strong>Signal Conversion:</strong> Rods and cones in the retina convert light into electrical signals.</li>
            <li><strong>Signal Transmission:</strong> The optic nerve carries these signals to the brain for interpretation.</li>
        </ul>

