    <h2 class="subtitle" id="vision-nocturnal-animals">2. Vision in Nocturnal Animals</h2>
    <div class="content">
        <h3>How Nocturnal Animals Perceive the World</h3>
        <p>Nocturnal animals such as owls and bats have evolved unique 
adaptations that allow them to thrive in low-light environments. These 
adaptations enhance their ability to locate prey, avoid predators, and 
navigate their surroundings.</p>

        <h4>Owls</h4>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Enhanced Rod Cells:</strong> Owls have a high density of rod cells in their retinas, enabling them to see in near darkness.</li>
            <li><strong>Facial Discs:</strong> The unique facial structure helps to funnel sound to their ears, enhancing auditory capabilities.</li>
            <li><strong>Large Eyes:</strong> Their large eyes maximize light capture and are positioned for a wide field of view.</li>
            <li><strong>Tapetum Lucidum:</strong> A reflective layer that increases night vision by bouncing light back through the retina.</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Bats</h4>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Echolocation:</strong> Bats primarily use 
echolocation for navigation and hunting, emitting high-frequency sounds 
and interpreting the returning echoes.</li>
            <li><strong>Large Ears:</strong> Many species have large ears that are highly sensitive to detect faint echoes.</li>
            <li><strong>High Rod Density:</strong> Like owls, bats have a high density of rod cells for improved night vision.</li>
            <li><strong>Adaptable Pupils:</strong> Bats can adjust their pupil size to optimize light intake.</li>
        </ul>

