    <h2 class="subtitle" id="remote-sensing-technologies">3. Remote Sensing Technologies Inspired by Nocturnal Animals</h2>
    <div class="content">
        <h3>Technological Emulation of Biological Systems</h3>
        <p>The unique adaptations of nocturnal animals have inspired 
advancements in remote sensing technologies. These technologies aim to 
replicate the capabilities that allow these animals to perceive their 
surroundings in low-light conditions.</p>

        <h4>Infrared Imaging</h4>
        <p>Infrared cameras detect heat emitted by objects, allowing 
visibility in complete darkness. This technology is akin to the thermal 
sensitivity found in some nocturnal animals.</p>
        
        <h4>Echolocation Technologies</h4>
        <p>Sonar systems and robotic navigation inspired by bat 
echolocation enable navigation and obstacle detection in low visibility,
 similar to how bats use sound waves.</p>

        <h4>Low-Light Cameras</h4>
        <p>Advanced cameras utilize technologies like image 
intensification to create clear images in dim conditions, mimicking the 
high sensitivity of nocturnal animal eyes.</p>

        <h4>Multispectral and Hyperspectral Imaging</h4>
        <p>These technologies analyze wavelengths beyond human vision, 
providing insights into materials and biological processes in low-light 
environments, inspired by the visual capabilities of nocturnal animals.</p>

        <h3>Comparative Designs</h3>
        <p>Several remote sensing technologies incorporate designs inspired by nocturnal animals:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Night Vision Goggles:</strong> Designed to enhance visibility in low-light conditions, mimicking the rod-dominated vision of nocturnal animals.</li>
            <li><strong>Echolocation Sensors:</strong> Used in robotics, these sensors operate similarly to bat echolocation, allowing machines to detect obstacles.</li>
            <li><strong>Thermal Cameras:</strong> These cameras, like 
the infrared vision of some nocturnal predators, detect heat signatures,
 providing valuable information in the dark.</li>
        </ul>

